    "summary": "The Kingdom of Pergamon (282–133 BC) was a small but prosperous Hellenistic kingdom in western Anatolia, centered on the acropolis city of Pergamon (modern Bergama in Turkey), which became one of the [[event:80|Hellenistic Period]]'s most remarkable cultural centers. Originally a Seleucid treasury city, it was seized by Philetaerus, a eunuch treasurer, who used its wealth to establish an independent dynasty, the Attalids.\n\nThe Attalids made Pergamon's name synonymous with cultural prestige through heavy investment in architecture, libraries, and art. The city's library was reputed to rival the [[event:1044|Library of Alexandria]]; according to ancient tradition, the Ptolemies cut off papyrus exports to prevent Pergamon's library from surpassing Alexandria's, forcing the Pergamenes to develop parchment (pergamene, from which the modern word derives). The Attalid kings cultivated Rome as an ally against the [[event:1041|Seleucid Empire]] and the [[event:1042|Antigonid Dynasty]], contributing to Rome's growing influence in the eastern Mediterranean. The last Attalid king, Attalus III, bequeathed the kingdom to Rome in 133 BC to prevent succession struggles, making Pergamon the province of Asia and vastly expanding Rome's eastern dominion.",
